metadata.title: Aristotle's Ethics - Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy
metadata.author: Richard Kraut

raw_content: Aristotle's Nicomachean Ethics is one of the most influential works in moral philosophy. The treatise examines the nature of virtue, the good life, and practical wisdom...

claims_identified: Virtue is a disposition to act in ways that promote human flourishing
The good life consists in the exercise of virtue in accordance with reason
Moral virtues are acquired through habituation and practice

connections_discovered.connection: Aristotelian virtue ethics influenced medieval Christian philosophy
Virtue ethics principles apply to modern psychology and well-being research

agent_recommendations.text_processor: High-quality academic content with clear structure
agent_recommendations.claim_analyzer: All claims verified against primary sources
agent_recommendations.concept_explorer: Rich connections to both historical and contemporary philosophy
